Understanding Employee Turnover

Employee Turnover refers to the phenomenon of an employee ending their formal relationship with an organization. In essence, it signifies the gradual loss or exit of employees over time. The terms - employee churn, employee turnover, and employee attrition - are often used interchangeably in the corporate domain.

Why Employee Turnover Matters?

Employees, being the cornerstone of an organization, accentuate its value. A predominant challenge that organizations grapple with today is employee retention. Alarmingly, a vast segment, almost a quarter of all U.S. workers, opts to resign annually. In specific sectors, this rate takes a dramatic leap. Citing the Society of Human Resource Management (SHRM), the financial implications of replacing an employee can range from 50-60% of the employees salary, with overarching costs surging to 90-200%.

Types of Employee Turnover

Employee turnover can be dichotomized into: - Voluntary Turnover: This transpires when an employee, on their volition, chooses to resign. - Involuntary Turnover: This is an organizational call, where the entity decides to release an employee. This could stem from contractual obligations, organizational restructuring, or disciplinary measures.

Hidden Reasons for Employee Turnover

Underlying reasons for exits often remain shrouded in mystery as employees generally refrain from disclosing them. This course promises revelations, unearthing hidden reasons that might propel turnover. Factors like relationships with superiors, recent salary revisions, extended working hours, commute duration, career satisfaction, and tenure could be pivotal.
